<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-396-720  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 396 720.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  June 1989 v21 n6 p57(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Critical issues face ISDN.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The upcoming ISDN combined voice-data communications standard maynot fulfill its promise because of technical and marketinghurdles.andP;  A major problem is the lack of universal standards forISDN's subscriber interface and for computer-to-PBXcommunications.andP;  Local-area networks (LANs) are also expected tobe firmly entrenched by the time ISDN matures in the 1990s,resulting in a severe technology gap which will hurt the ISDNmarket.andP;  Debate is still raging over whether ISDN should be basedon satellite communications or fiber-optic technology.andP;  Separatestandards have been proposed for terrestrial and satellite ISDNcircuits, resulting in incompatible time-delay characteristics.andO;High cost is another factor inhibiting ISDN.andP;  Station equipmentnow costs $600 to $1,000 per set, and ISDN service is expected tocost 1.5 times as much as conventional telephone service.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ISDNConnectivityCommunications TechnologyFuture TechnologiesStandardsLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>